The paper deals with unsupervised learning from videos using deep neural networks, which is a topic that falls under computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG). The proposed Siamese architectures and loss functions are designed to learn discriminative features from unlabeled videos, which is a problem in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The evaluation of the proposed models involves discovering actions and scenes in video collections, which is a task in multimedia (cs.MM). Finally, the paper also discusses the benefits of using unsupervised learning as a prior for supervised recognition tasks, which is a topic in information retrieval (cs.IR).
